<h2>Data Source and Methodology</h2>
<p>All calculations are based on the formulas and data provided by the official Japanese pension guidelines and are aligned with the latest government updates.</p>
<h2>The Formula Explained</h2>
<div class="formula-box">
                \[
                \text{Pension} = \text{Years of Contribution} \times \text{Average Monthly Salary} \times \text{Pension Rate}
                \]
            </div>
<h2>Glossary of Terms</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Years of Contribution:</strong> The number of years you have contributed to the pension system.</li>
<li><strong>Average Monthly Salary:</strong> Average salary used to calculate pension benefits.</li>
<li><strong>Pension Rate:</strong> The rate applied according to the pension plan.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
<div>
<h3>What is the Japanese Pension system?</h3>
<p>The Japanese Pension system is a government-managed scheme providing retirement, disability, and survivor benefits.</p>
<h3>How are the pension benefits calculated?</h3>
<p>Pension benefits are calculated based on your years of contribution, average salary, and the current pension rate.</p>
<h3>Can foreigners receive Japanese pension?</h3>
<p>Yes, foreigners who have contributed to the system for more than 10 years are eligible to receive pension benefits.</p>
<h3>How can I increase my pension amount?</h3>
<p>Increasing your years of contribution and maintaining a higher average salary can increase your pension benefits.</p>
<h3>What happens if I leave Japan before retirement?</h3>
<p>You may be eligible for a lump-sum withdrawal payment under certain conditions.</p>
</div>
